Wendy Espinoza Camejo

Bio📔

Hello everyone, my name is Wendy. I am a PhD - candidate in the Human Genetics and Genomics program at the Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine. My thesis focuses on understanding the underlying mechanism of aneurysm development in Autosomal Recessive Cutis Laxa type 1B syndrome, a tissue connective disorder affecting young children. My research interests include vascular biology, cardiovascular disease, tissue connective disorder, Mendelian disease, and prenatal development. I am originally from the Dominican Republic 🇩🇴 and moved to Maryland during my last year of high school. During this transition, I discovered my passion for science 🧬 and decided to study Biology at Morgan State University. I am familiar with R and, to a lesser extent, Python. I acquired some data analysis experience by analyzing scRNA-seq and bulk RNA-seq data. I took Statistics for Laboratory Scientists. I hope to learn more about R, familiarize myself with Git and GitHub, and learn how to use these tools for collaboration and data organization.

I love to watch movies🎥, food🌮, and travel with my family✈️👨‍👩‍👧.

Education🎓

Johns Hopkins University | Baltimore, MD

Ph.D. in Human Genetics and Genomics | August 20202 - present

Morgan State University | Baltimore, MD

B.S. in Biology | August 2016 - June 2020

Fun Facts😁

  • I’ve been told that I can talk a lot.
  • I sing when I am mad.
  • My best school work was done while watching TV in bed.
  • Many people think I can’t cook, but I am an excellent cook.
  • I am terrible at making jokes and telling stories.
